# iOS Port Prototype

Currently, the iOS port prototype cannot easily be built in the same way as we
build and run applications for other platforms.

This project currently loads XUL through mozglue and then starts `XRE_main` like
we do on desktop, handling full control over to XUL. This is the same as the
original approach which was removed in
https://phabricator.services.mozilla.com/D25800, and the code is heavily
inspired by that old project.

## Building

1. Update the .mozconfig to be as it is described below. Some things like the
   OBJDIR are hard-coded in the xcode project file currently, so need to be
   configured correctly.

2. Build the main core of XUL with `./mach build` as normal.

3. Once the build is finished, open the xcode project, and attempt to run the
   project in the iOS simulator.

   The build script in the xcode project will copy the relevant files from the objdir into the final bundle's path

### .mozconfig

The following is a .mozconfig which can be used to build a debug iOS simulator
version of the iOS prototype on an apple-silicon macbook.

```
# Enable this target application.
# Note that this only actually builds the libraries (i.e.  XUL), and doesn't
# actually build a full iOS application.
ac_add_options --enable-application=mobile/ios

# Tests like c++ unit tests aren't working on iOS yet, so we need to disable
# building them.
ac_add_options --disable-tests

# The `DEBUG` status of XUL needs to match the debug status of the xcode
# project. Given that you're probably running in the emulator in debug mode -
# you'll need `--enable-debug`.
ac_add_options --enable-debug

# In order to target the iOS simulator, you need to explicitly specify an iOS
# simulator target. This is the target to use on apple silicon, I haven't tried
# building on an x86-64 macbook,
ac_add_options --target=aarch64-apple-ios-sim

# Unfortunately the OBJDIR is hard-coded in the xcode project file right now, so
# you'll need to build with specifically this objdir path.
mk_add_options MOZ_OBJDIR=@TOPSRCDIR@/obj-firefox
```
